          "title": "The interrogation in reverse, the judgment in order (3:8-19)",
          "body": "When the LORD God walks in the garden, the order of His pursuit is theologically careful. He calls **the man** first (3:9) — the covenant head bears first responsibility. The man blames the woman (and implicitly God: 'the woman *whom You gave me*'). The LORD then turns to the **woman** (3:13), who blames the serpent. The LORD does not question the **serpent** at all — there is no redemption available for him — He moves straight to sentence. But notice the reversal: the order of interrogation runs man → woman → serpent (reverse order of sin), while the order of sentencing runs serpent → woman → man (original order of sin). The serpent is cursed first and most absolutely; the woman receives a curse on her two most distinctive vocations, motherhood and marriage; the man receives a curse on his vocation of dominion over the earth. Each judgment targets the specific gift each party had received in creation."
