        "number": 5,
        "title": "Eve, garments, and exile — faith, sacrifice, and the guarded way",
        "range": "3:20-24",
        "excerpt": "The LORD God made garments of skin for Adam and his wife, and clothed them.",
        "body": "Between the death sentence (3:19) and the expulsion (3:23), three small but decisive acts of grace occur. They are easy to miss because the chapter's emotional weight is on the curses, but they carry the gospel.\n\n**First** (3:20), Adam names his wife. *'Now the man called his wife's name Eve, because she was the mother of all the living.'* This is astonishing in context. God has just announced that Adam is dust and will return to dust. By every natural reckoning, the species is about to die out — they are under sentence of death, exiled from the tree of life, and have no children. Yet Adam responds to the death sentence by giving his wife a name (Hebrew *chavvah*, from the root *chay*, 'to live') that confesses she will bear children and life will continue. This is an act of **faith**. Adam has heard the promise of seed in 3:15, and he believes God's word more than the death sentence in 3:19. Eve is the first name given on the basis of a divine promise — the same kind of faith Abraham will exercise when he names Isaac (Genesis 21:3) and that Mary will exercise when she names Jesus (Luke 1:31). The naming of Eve is the first human act of gospel-shaped faith in Scripture.\n\n**Second** (3:21), God Himself does what the humans could not do. Their fig leaves (3:7) are inadequate because self-made coverings cannot atone for guilt before a holy God. *'The LORD God made garments of skin for Adam and his wife, and clothed them.'* Two implications are inescapable. First, an animal died. This is the first recorded death in Scripture, and it is a substitutionary death — the innocent dies so the guilty can be clothed. Second, **God** does the clothing. He kills the animal, He fashions the garments (Hebrew *asah* — the same verb used of His creative work in Genesis 1), and He puts them on the humans. The entire Old Testament sacrificial system is anticipated here in seed form: an innocent victim, blood shed, covering provided by God for the guilty. Hebrews 9:22 codifies what Genesis 3:21 first enacts — 'without shedding of blood there is no forgiveness.' Paul brings the imagery to its climax: those who have been clothed with Christ (Galatians 3:27) are clothed in garments fashioned at infinitely greater cost than the first.\n\n**Third** (3:22-24), the exile itself is interpreted as mercy. *'Behold, the man has become like one of Us, knowing good and evil; and now, he might stretch out his hand, and take also from the tree of life, and eat, and live forever.'* The plural 'one of Us' echoes the plural deliberations of 1:26 ('Let Us make man in Our image') — a Trinitarian intimation that the New Testament will unfold. The serpent's promise of being 'like God, knowing good and evil' (3:5) is acknowledged by God Himself as having come true (3:22). But the parenthetical *and now* (Hebrew *ve'attah*) signals decisive action: if the humans eat from the tree of life *now*, in their fallen state, they will be eternally trapped in their fallenness. Death, paradoxically, must be possible for redemption to be possible. The expulsion from the garden is therefore an act of severe mercy — God forecloses the possibility of immortal fallenness so that mortal fallenness can one day become immortal righteousness.\n\nThe chapter's final image (3:24) is the cherubim with the flaming sword guarding the way to the tree of life. These cherubim will reappear over the ark of the covenant (Exodus 25:18-22), embroidered on the veil that separates the holy place from the Most Holy Place (Exodus 26:31), and again in Ezekiel's temple visions. The cherubim are God's heavenly attendants who guard His holy presence — and they are stationed in Genesis 3:24 for exactly the reason they will be stationed over the ark: God's holiness cannot be casually approached by sinners. But notice the verb: they 'guard the way' (Hebrew *shamar* — to keep, watch, preserve). The verb does not say they *destroyed* the way; the way still exists, guarded. The whole biblical narrative from this point is the LORD opening that guarded way in stages — through sacrifice, through tabernacle, through temple, and finally through the torn veil of Matthew 27:51 when the cherubim step aside and the way to the tree of life is opened at last. Revelation 22:2 closes the canon with the redeemed eating from the tree of life unhindered — Genesis 3:24 reversed.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chavvah* (Eve, 3:20) is from the root *chay* (life, living) — a name that confesses faith in the seed-promise just announced. *Asah* (made, 3:21) is the same verb of divine making used in Genesis 1; God's clothing of Adam and Eve is portrayed as a creative act, like the original creation. *Or* (skin, 3:21) is the same Hebrew word later used for the leather/skin coverings of the tabernacle (Exodus 26:14) — the tabernacle is, among other things, a portable Eden. *Shamar* (guard, 3:24) is the same verb God used in 2:15 commanding Adam to *guard* the garden — Adam failed to guard the garden against the serpent, so now cherubim guard it against Adam."
